I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
Firstly, I urge all members of the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, particularly the nuclear powers, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and engage in negotiations on effective measures that will lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
They could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has been proposed for a long time within the UN.
I have circulated a draft of such a convention to all UN member states, providing a good starting point.
The nuclear powers should engage actively with this issue at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiating forum on disarmament worldwide, together with other states.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the US and Russia, aimed at significantly and verifiably reducing their arsenals.
Governments should also invest more in control research and development.
Britain's proposal to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the issue of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues within the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly reassure states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not become victims of a nuclear weapons deployment or the threat of it.
The Security Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and take on their own disarmament obligations.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials should only be allowed to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the nuclear test ban treaty into effect, as well as incentives to prompt the disarmament conference to take up discussions on a treaty on fissile materials immediately and without preconditions.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly advocate for efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
I urge all members of the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to promptly conclude their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily implement the stricter safety provisions of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they are doing to achieve these goals.
But these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to request that the nuclear powers submit such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no authoritative estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various additional measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, new efforts against terrorism involving weapons of mass destruction, limiting the production and trade of conventional weapons, and new arms bans, including for missiles and space weapons.
If there are genuine, confirmed progress in disarmament, the capability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons of the world and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks involving weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a fresh start, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
